s in Canada -- tPart III: Domestic Law Perspectives -- t13 Beyond Van der Peet: Bringing Together International, Indigenous and Constitutional Law -- t14 UNDRIP and the Move to the Nation-to-Nation Relationship -- t15 Options for Implementing UNDRIP without Creating Another Empty Box -- t16 Asserted vs. Established Rights and the Promise of UNDRIP -- t17 Articles 27 and 46(2): UNDRIP Signposts Pointing beyond the Justifiable-infringement Morass of Section 35 -- t18 Strategizing UNDRIP Implementation: Some Fundamentals -- t19 UNDRIP Implementation, Intercultural Learning and Substantive Engagement with Indigenous Legal Orders -- tPart IV: Concluding Thoughts -- t20 Implementation of UNDRIP within Canadian and Indigenous Law: Assessing Challenges -- t21 Conflicts or Complementarity with Domestic Systems? UNDRIP, Aboriginal Law and the Future of International Norms in Canada -- t22 UNDRIP as a Catalyst for Aboriginal and Treaty Rights Implementation and Reconciliation -- t23 The Necessity of Exploring Inherent Dignity in Indigenous Knowledge Systems -- tContributors -- tArtist Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImplementation in Canada of the United Nations Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples (UNDRIP) is a pivotal opportunity to explore the relationship between international law, Indigenous peoples' own laws, and Canada's constitutional narratives.Two significant statements by the current Liberal government - the May 2016 address by Indigenous Affairs Minister Carolyn Bennett to the Permanent Forum on Indigenous Issues at the United Nations and the September 2017 address to the United Nations by Prime Minister Justin Trudeau - have endorsed UNDRIP and committed Canada to implementing it as “a way forward” on the path to genuine nation-to-nation relationships with Indigenous peoples. In response, these essays engage with the legal, historical, political, and practical aspects of UNDRIP implementation. Written by Indigenous legal scholars and policy leaders, and guided by the metaphor of braiding international, domestic, and Indigenous laws into a strong, unified whole composed of distinct parts, the book makes visible the possibilities for reconciliation from different angles and under different lenses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aIndians of North AmericaxCivil rightszCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 0aIndigenous peoples (International law). 0aIndigenous peoplesxCivil rightszCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etczCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLegal status, laws, etc.zCanada. 7aLAW / Civil Rights.2bisacsh1 aAskew, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaton, Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrows, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBorrows, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChartrand, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartrand, Larry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChristie, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraft, Aimée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzgerald, Oonagh E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFitzgerald, Oonagh E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGunn, Brenda L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamilton, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHewitt, Jeffery G., econtributor.4ctb4https://